      "content": "i hear u, but \"accommodation\" sounds like a way to just control how they practice instead of actually letting them follow their faith. if a group says a specific law is fundamentally against their religion, and the state says \"no, you have to follow it or else,\" isn't the state basically just saying that secular law is more important than their actual right to believe? it feels like one side is being treated as more \"legitimate\" than the other. isn't that just picking a side?",
